    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Meaning literally pondweed, or water plant, well (Kroll 2015, 584-585), in pre-modern Chinese literature, zaojing 藻井 refers to a flat or recessed decorative ceiling which is based on an orthogonal grid and obscures the roof frame.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000290/ATTCAT</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109161/ATTCAT database (2018-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>藻井,在中國古代文獻中指的是一種具有井幹元素的用以遮蔽屋架的裝飾構造，既包含平的形式，也包括向上凹入或拱起的形式。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000290/ATTCAT</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109161/ATTCAT database (2018-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Significando literalmente lagoa, ou planta aquática, bem (Kroll 2015, 584-585), na literatura chinesa pré-moderna, zaojing refere-se a um teto decorativo plano ou recuado que se baseia em uma grade ortogonal e obscurece a estrutura do telhado.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109633/CVAA-BR Consortium (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
